elationships between the various parties who have contributed to the Superman mythos, including corporate executives, comics writers, artists, nostalgic commentators, and collectors. Armed with an encyclopedic knowledge of Superman’s appearances in comics and other media, Gordon also digs into comics archives to reveal the prominent role that fans have played in remembering, interpreting, and reimagining Superman’s iconography. Gordon considers how comics, film, and TV producers have taken advantage of fan engagement and nostalgia when selling Superman products. Investigating a character who is equally an icon of American culture, fan culture, and consumer culture, Superman thus offers a provocative analysis of mythmaking in the modern era.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aComic books, strips, etczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aHeroes in mass media. 0aMyth in mass media. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSuperheroesxSocial aspects. 0aSuperman (Comic strip). 4acape. 4aclark kent. 4acomic book. 4ahall of justice. 4ajustice league. 4akrypton. 4akryptonite. 4alex luthor. 4alois lane. 4aman of steel. 4asuper. 4asuperhero. 4asuperman movie. 4asuperman. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358754740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813587547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813587547.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  RUP eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK